{"title_page": "The Brother of Daphne", "text_new": "{{short description|1914 short story collection by Dornford Yates}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name         = The Brother of Daphne\n| image        = The Brother of Daphne 1942 reprint.jpg\n| caption      = 1942 Ward Lock reprint\n| author       = [[Dornford Yates]]\n| genre        =  Short stories\n| publisher    = [[Ward Lock & Co]]<ref name=\"BLcat\">{{Cite web |url=http://primocat.bl.uk/F?func=direct&local_base=ITEMV&doc_number=003995523&con_lng=eng |title=British Library Item details |website=primocat.bl.uk |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n| release_date = 1914<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n| media_type   = Print \n| pages        = 304<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n| preceded_by       = \n| followed_by       = [[The Courts of Idleness]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Brother of Daphne''''' is a 1914 collection of comic short stories by the English author [[Dornford Yates]] (Cecil William Mercer), the first book published under the [[Pen name|pen name]] he had been using for magazine pieces since 1910. This was also the first book to feature the group of characters that featured in many of his future works: Bertram ('Berry') Pleydell, his wife and cousin Daphne Pleydell, Daphne's brother Boy Pleydell, another cousin Jonathan ('Jonah') Mansel, and Jonah's younger sister Jill Mansel.  The group of five - Berry, Daphne, Boy, Jonah and Jill - later came to be known collectively as 'Berry and Co'.{{sfn|Usborne|1974|pp=28-29}}\n\nThe short stories in the collection were originally published in ''[[The Windsor Magazine]]'',{{sfn|Smithers|1982|loc=Appendix I}} their publication in book form having been suggested to Mercer by the ''Windsor'''s editor Arthur Hutchinson.{{sfn|Smithers|1982|p=78}}\n\n== Plot ==\nFifteen short stories recounting the comic adventures of Boy, Daphne, Berry, Jonah and Jill, set in [[Hampshire]], [[Devon]], [[Cotswolds|The Cotswolds]], and [[Austria]]. They are narrated in the first person by Boy.\n\n== Chapters == \n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|+\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chapter\n! scope=\"col\" | Book Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Windsor Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Volume\n! scope=\"col\" | Issue\n! scope=\"col\" | Pages\n! scope=\"col\" | Illustrator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| Punch And Judy\n| Punch And Judy\n| October 1911\n| XXXIV\n| 202\n| 541-551\n| H Radcliffe-Wilson\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| Clothes And The Man\n| There Is A Tide\n| August 1913\n| XXXVIII\n| 224\n| 263-271\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| When It Was Dark\n| A Drive In The Dark\n| November 1911\n| XXXIV\n| 203\n| 669-676\n| Fred Pegram\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| Adam And New Year's Eve\n| Fair Exchange\n| January 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 229\n| 209-218\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| The Judgement of Paris\n| The Judgement of Paris\n| June 1914\n| XL\n| 234\n| 79-86\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| Which To Adore\n| Which To Adore\n| March 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 231\n| 486-494\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| Every Picture Tells A Story\n| Every Picture Tells A Story\n| July 1914\n| XL\n| 235\n| 201-208\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| The Busy Beers\n| Busy Bees\n| September 1911\n| XXXIV\n| 201\n| 391-398\n| A Wallis Mills\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| A Point Of Honour\n| A Point Of Honour\n| October 1913\n| XXXVIII\n| 226\n| 501-507\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| Pride Goeth Before\n| Pride Goeth Before\n| April 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 232\n| 672-678\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| The Love Scene\n| The Love Scene\n| September 1913\n| XXXVIII\n| 225\n| 383-391\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| The Order Of The Bath\n| The Order Of The Bath\n| May 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 233\n| 685-693\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n| A Lucid Interval\n| A Lucid Interval\n| November 1913\n| XXXVIII\n| 227\n| 621-627\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n| A Private View\n| A Private View\n| July 1913\n| XXXVIII\n| 223\n| 141-148\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n| All Found\n| All Found\n| February 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 230\n| 371-378\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n|}\n\n== Illustrations ==\n\nThe first edition of the book, published in 1914, included plates of the illustrations by George Cecil Wilmhurst (1873-1930), originally included in the Windsor Magazine serialisations, for the stories included as chapters 2, 4, 6, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14 and 15. The illustration from Chapter 15 \"All Found\" was also used on the dustjacket of the first edition. Wilmhurst's illustrations for chapters 5 and 7, and the illustrations by the three artists from the 1911 serialisations, were not included in the book. The book was reprinted in 1920 and that and subsequent editions did not include any illustrations.\n\n== Critical reception ==\nThe book was reviewed favourably by ''[[Punch (magazine)|Punch]]'' in August 1914. The reviewer called the stories \"agreeable nonsense\", in which the narrator \"apparently could not go out for the simplest walk without meeting some amiable young woman, divinely fair and supernaturally witty, with whom he presently exchanged airy badinage\".<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=19 August 1914 |title=Our Booking-Office. (By Mr Punch's Staff of Learned Clerks)\n |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/26969/26969-h/26969-h.htm |magazine=Punch}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|title=Dornford Yates |last= Smithers |first=AJ |publisher=[[Hodder & Stoughton|Hodder and Stoughton]] |year=1982 |location=London |isbn=0 340 27547 2}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|title=Clubland Heroes |last= Usborne |first=Richard |publisher=Barrie & Jenkins |year=1974 |location=London |isbn=0 214 20012 4}}\n\n[[Category:1914 short story collections]]\n[[Category:Ward Lock & Co books]]\n[[Category:Short story collections by Dornford Yates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1914 short story collection by Dornford Yates}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name         = The Brother of Daphne\n| image        = The Brother of Daphne 1942 reprint.jpg\n| caption      = 1942 Ward Lock reprint\n| author       = [[Dornford Yates]]\n| genre        =  Short stories\n| publisher    = [[Ward Lock & Co]]<ref name=\"BLcat\">{{Cite web |url=http://primocat.bl.uk/F?func=direct&local_base=ITEMV&doc_number=003995523&con_lng=eng |title=British Library Item details |website=primocat.bl.uk |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n| release_date = 1914<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n| media_type   = Print \n| pages        = 304<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n| preceded_by       = \n| followed_by       = [[The Courts of Idleness]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Brother of Daphne''''' is a 1914 collection of comic short stories by the English author [[Dornford Yates]] (Cecil William Mercer), the first book published under the [[Pen name|pen name]] he had been using for magazine pieces since 1910. This was also the first book to feature the group of characters that featured in many of his future works: Bertram ('Berry') Pleydell, his wife and cousin Daphne Pleydell, Daphne's brother Boy Pleydell, another cousin Jonathan ('Jonah') Mansel, and Jonah's younger sister Jill Mansel.  The group of five - Berry, Daphne, Boy, Jonah and Jill - later came to be known collectively as 'Berry and Co'.{{sfn|Usborne|1974|pp=28-29}}\nThe short stories in the collection were originally published in ''[[The Windsor Magazine]]'',{{sfn|Smithers|1982|loc=Appendix I}} their publication in book form having been suggested to Mercer by the ''Windsor'''s editor Arthur Hutchinson.{{sfn|Smithers|1982|p=78}}\n\n== Plot ==\nFifteen short stories recounting the comic adventures of Boy, Daphne, Berry, Jonah and Jill, set in [[Hampshire]], [[Devon]], [[Cotswolds|The Cotswolds]], and [[Austria]]. They are narrated in the first person by Boy.\n\n== Chapters == \n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|+\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chapter\n! scope=\"col\" | Book Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Windsor Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Volume\n! scope=\"col\" | Issue\n! scope=\"col\" | Pages\n! scope=\"col\" | Illustrator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| Punch And Judy\n| Punch And Judy\n| October 1911\n| XXXIV\n| 202\n| 541-551\n| H Radcliffe-Wilson\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| Clothes And The Man\n| There Is A Tide\n| August 1913\n| XXXVIII\n| 224\n| 263-271\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| When It Was Dark\n| A Drive In The Dark\n| November 1911\n| XXXIV\n| 203\n| 669-676\n| Fred Pegram\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| Adam And New Year's Eve\n| Fair Exchange\n| January 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 229\n| 209-218\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| The Judgement of Paris\n| The Judgement of Paris\n| June 1914\n| XL\n| 234\n| 79-86\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| Which To Adore\n| Which To Adore\n| March 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 231\n| 486-494\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| Every Picture Tells A Story\n| Every Picture Tells A Story\n| July 1914\n| XL\n| 235\n| 201-208\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| The Busy Beers\n| Busy Bees\n| September 1911\n| XXXIV\n| 201\n| 391-398\n| A Wallis Mills\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| A Point Of Honour\n| A Point Of Honour\n| October 1913\n| XXXVIII\n| 226\n| 501-507\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| Pride Goeth Before\n| Pride Goeth Before\n| April 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 232\n| 672-678\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| The Love Scene\n| The Love Scene\n| September 1913\n| XXXVIII\n| 225\n| 383-391\n| G C Wilmhurst\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| The Order Of The Bath\n| The Order Of The Bath\n| May 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 233\n| 685-693\n