{"title_page": "WKTA", "text_new": "{{Infobox Radio station\n| name                 = WKTA\n| image                = WKTA logo.jpg\n| image_size           = 200px\n| city                 = [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston]], [[Illinois]]\n| area                 = \n| slogan               =\n| branding             = ''New Life Russian Radio''<br>''the zone 95.9/1330'' \n| frequency            = 1330 [[kHz]] AM\n| repeater             = \n| airdate              = [[1953 in radio|1953]]<ref name=\"BCYearbook1971\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1971/B-1-Radio-YB-1971.pdf 1971 Broadcasting Yearbook]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]], 1971. p. B-63. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref>\n| share                = \n| share as of          =  \n| share source         =  \n| format               = Multicultural Ethnic<br>[[Sports radio|Sports Talk]]\n| power                = 5,000 [[watt]]s day<br>110 [[watt]]s night\n| erp                  = \n| haat                 = \n| class                = D\n| facility_id          = 52909\n| coordinates          = {{coord|42|8|23|N|87|53|9|W|region:US_type:city}}\n| callsign_meaning     = \n| former_callsigns     = WEAW (1953-1979)<ref name=\"HistoryCards\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=66273 History Cards for WKTA], fcc.gov. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><br>WPRZ (1979<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/>-1981)<ref name=\"CallSign\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=52909&Callsign=WKTA52909 Call Sign History], fcc.gov. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><br>WEAW (1981-1987)<ref name=\"CallSign\"/><br>WSSY (1987-1990)<ref name=\"CallSign\"/>\n| owner                = Polnet Communications, Ltd.\n| licensee             = \n| sister_stations      = [[WEEF]], [[WNVR]], [[WPJX]], [[WRDZ (AM)|WRDZ]]\n| webcast              = \n| website              = \n| affiliations         = \n}}\n\n'''WKTA''' (1330 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]) is a [[radio station]]  broadcasting [[Ethnic|Multicultural ethnic]] and [[News Talk]] formats. Licensed to [[Evanston, Illinois]], United States, the station serves the Chicago area. The station is currently owned by Polnet Communications, Ltd.<ref name=\"FCC\">{{cite web|url=https://transition.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/amq?list=0&facid=52909 |title=WKTA Facility Record |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division |access-date=August 11, 2015}}</ref> The transmitter's power is 5,000 watts, and the station covers the city of Chicago and the Northern suburbs.<ref name=\"FCC\"/><ref>[http://radio-locator.com/cgi-bin/pat?call=WKTA&service=AM&status=L&hours=D  Predicted daytime coverage area for WKTA 1330 AM, Evanston, IL], radio-locator. Accessed August 11, 2015</ref>\n\n==FM Translator==\nIn addition to the main signal on 1330 [[kHz]], the WKTA signal is also heard on 95.9 [[MHz]], an [[FM translator]].\n{{RadioTranslators\n|callsign        = WKTA\n|call1           = W240DE\n|freq1           = 95.9\n|fid1            = 147928\n|watts1          = 80\n|haat1           = 44\n|class1          = D\n|city1           = Evanston, Illinois\n}}\n\n==History==\nThe station began broadcasting in 1953, holding the call sign WEAW.<ref name=\"BCYearbook1971\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1971/B-1-Radio-YB-1971.pdf 1971 Broadcasting Yearbook]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]], 1971. p. B-63. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> The station was owned by North Shore Broadcasting, and the station's call sign stood for its president Edward A. Wheeler.<ref name=\"Ghrist\"/><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Station-Albums/Chicago-Trib-1979-Mar-About-Chi-Radio.pdf What those letters on the dial mean]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune Magazine]]''. March 4, 1979. p. 16. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> The station's transmitter was located in Evanston and it ran 500 watts during daytime hours only.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> In 1956, the station's power was increased to 1,000 watts.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> By 1959, the station had begun airing brokered ethnic programming.<ref name=\"Ghrist\">Ghrist, John R. (1996). ''Valley Voices: A Radio History''. Crossroads Communications. p. 318-321.</ref> In 1962, the station's transmitter was moved to an unincorporated area between [[Northbrook, Illinois|Northbrook]] and [[Wheeling, Illinois|Wheeling]], and its power was increased to 5,000 watts.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> By the early 1970s the station primarily aired brokered ethnic and religious programs.<ref name=\"Ghrist\"/>\n\nBy early 1979 the station had begun airing a [[Christian contemporary]] format.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Station-Albums/Chicago-Trib-1979-Mar-About-Chi-Radio.pdf Stations, everywhere: a listeners' guide to the AM and FM bands]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune Magazine]]''. March 4, 1979. p. 34. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> On June 1, 1979, the station's call sign was later changed to WPRZ.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> On July 14, 1979, WPRZ presented the Christian contemporary festival \"Alleluia\", which featured [[Chuck Girard]].<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1979/Billboard%201979-06-30.pdf 'Alleluia' On Air]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. June 30, 1979. p. 20. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> The station was taken off the air in autumn of 1980.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/><ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1980s/1980/RR-1980-12-12.pdf '80 In Review]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]'', Issue Number 362, December 12, 1980. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn late 1981, the license was sold to Lee Hague for $125,000.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1981/1981-10-05-BC.pdf Ownership Changes]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. October 5, 1981. p. 59. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> The following year the station was brought back on the air from a new site in the same area, with the WEAW callsign revived.<ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/comment.pl?Application_id=31934&File_number=BMP-19810702AI Public Notice Comment - BMP-19810702AI], fcc.gov. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/comment.pl?Application_id=39083&File_number=BL-19820203AF Public Notice Comment - BL-19820203AF], fcc.gov. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"CallSign\"/> The station aired [[adult contemporary]] music and religious programming.<ref name=\"Ghrist\"/><ref name=\"BCYearbook1983\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1983/B-Radio-Ala-Mt-1983-YB.pdf Broadcasting/Cablecasting Yearbook 1983]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting/Cablecasting]], 1983. p. B-73. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> By the mid-1980s the station was airing [[Christian talk and teaching]] programs and uptempo [[Christian contemporary music]], with a certain amount of secular adult contemporary mixed in.<ref>[[Eric Zorn|Zorn, Eric]]. \"[https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1985-04-14-8501210777-story.html Religious Radio Wades To Mainstream To Pull Listeners To Its Message]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. April 14, 1985. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"ChiRadioGuide\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/Chicago_Magazine/Chicago-Radio-Guide-May-1985.pdf Chicago Radio Guide]''. Vol. 1, No. 1. May 1985. Retrieved September 10, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Ghrist\"/> Christian talk and teaching programs heard on WEAW included ''[[The Old-Time Gospel Hour]]'' with [[Jerry Falwell]], ''Family Altar'' with [[Lester Roloff]], and ''[[Insight for Living]]'' with [[Chuck Swindoll]].<ref name=\"ChiRadioGuide\"/>\n\nIn 1986, the station was sold to Polnet Communications for $1.2 million.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1986/BC-1986-02-17.pdf Changing Hands]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. February 17, 1986. p. 71. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> The station would air adult contemporary music, along with a large amount of ethnic programming.<ref name=\"BCYearbook1987\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1987/B1-BC-YB-1987.pdf Broadcasting/Cablecasting Yearbook 1987]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting/Cablecasting]], 1987. p. B-89. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> In October 1987, the station's callsign was changed to WSSY.<ref name=\"CallSign\"/> The station was branded \"Sunny 1330\".<ref>''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/City-Magazines-Misc/Chicagoland-Radio-Waves-Two-Issues.pdf Chicagoland Radio Waves: Your Complete Guide to Local Radio]''. Media Ties. Summer 1988. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"Ghrist\"/>\n\nIn 1989, WSSY began to air a [[hard rock]] and [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] format branded \"G-Force\", though brokered ethnic and religious programming continued to air mornings and early afternoons.<ref>Seigenthaler, Katherine. \"[https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1990-04-03-9001270499-story.html Heavy Mettle]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. April 3, 1990. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/Chicago_Magazine/Chicago-1989-Fall.pdf WSSY AM 1330]\", ''Radio Chicago''. Fall 1989. p. 28. Retrieved January 20, 2019.</ref> In 1990 the station's call letters were changed to WKTA.<ref name=\"CallSign\"/> By early 1991, \"G-Force\" had ended, and the station aired brokered ethnic and religious programming.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/Chicago_Magazine/Chicago-1991-Winter.pdf WKTA AM 1330]\", ''Radio Chicago''. p. 41. Winter 1991. Retrieved January 20, 2019.</ref> The hard rock and heavy metal format would again appear on WKTA as \"Rebel Radio\", a brokered format launched by G-Force alumni Scott Davidson.<ref>[http://www.g-forceradio.zoomshare.com/ Chicago Radio Rock Wars: G-Force 1330] Accessed January 1, 2014</ref> WKTA would become a flagship station for the hard rock network, which was syndicated to other stations in the midwest. New Life Russian Radio broadcast from [[Northbrook, Illinois]] on 1330 AM WKTA, featuring call-in shows, international news, and European music.<ref>Gwinn, Eric. \"[https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2003-05-02-0305020006-story.html Russian picnic mixes borscht with flavor of the homeland]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. May 2, 2003. Retrieved April 15, 2020.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.facebook.com/pg/ShawnAndMaya/about/ thezone 95.9/1330 Facebook]\n{{AM station data|WKTA}}\n\n{{Chicago Radio}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Radio stations in Chicago|KTA]]\n[[Category:Russian-language radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:German-language radio stations]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language radio stations in Illinois|KTA]]\n[[Category:Foreign-language radio stations in Illinois|KTA]]\n[[Category:Russian-language media in the United States]]\n[[Category:German-language media in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1953]]\n[[Category:1953 establishments in Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Radio station\n| name                 = WKTA\n| image                = WKTA logo.jpg\n| image_size           = 200px\n| city                 = [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston]], [[Illinois]]\n| area                 = \n| slogan               =\n| branding             = ''New Life Russian Radio''<br>''the zone 95.9/1330'' \n| frequency            = 1330 [[kHz]] AM\n| repeater             = \n| airdate              = [[1953 in radio|1953]]<ref name=\"BCYearbook1971\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1971/B-1-Radio-YB-1971.pdf 1971 Broadcasting Yearbook]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]], 1971. p. B-63. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref>\n| share                = \n| share as of          =  \n| share source         =  \n| format               = Multicultural Ethnic<br>[[Sports radio|Sports Talk]]\n| power                = 5,000 [[watt]]s day<br>110 [[watt]]s night\n| erp                  = \n| haat                 = \n| class                = D\n| facility_id          = 52909\n| coordinates          = {{coord|42|8|23|N|87|53|9|W|region:US_type:city}}\n| callsign_meaning     = \n| former_callsigns     = WEAW (1953-1979)<ref name=\"HistoryCards\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=66273 History Cards for WKTA], fcc.gov. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><br>WPRZ (1979<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/>-1981)<ref name=\"CallSign\">[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=52909&Callsign=WKTA52909 Call Sign History], fcc.gov. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><br>WEAW (1981-1987)<ref name=\"CallSign\"/><br>WSSY (1987-1990)<ref name=\"CallSign\"/>\n| owner                = Polnet Communications, Ltd.\n| licensee             = \n| sister_stations      = [[WEEF]], [[WNVR]], [[WPJX]], [[WRDZ (AM)|WRDZ]]\n| webcast              = \n| website              = \n| affiliations         = \n}}\n\n'''WKTA''' (1330 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]) is a [[radio station]]  broadcasting [[Ethnic|Multicultural ethnic]] and [[News Talk]] formats. Licensed to [[Evanston, Illinois]], United States, the station serves the Chicago area. The station is currently owned by Polnet Communications, Ltd.<ref name=\"FCC\">{{cite web|url=https://transition.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/amq?list=0&facid=52909 |title=WKTA Facility Record |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division |access-date=August 11, 2015}}</ref> The transmitter's power is 5,000 watts, and the station covers the city of Chicago and the Northern suburbs.<ref name=\"FCC\"/><ref>[http://radio-locator.com/cgi-bin/pat?call=WKTA&service=AM&status=L&hours=D  Predicted daytime coverage area for WKTA 1330 AM, Evanston, IL], radio-locator. Accessed August 11, 2015</ref>\n\n==FM Translator==\nIn addition to the main signal on 1330 [[kHz]], the WKTA signal is also heard on 95.9 [[MHz]], an [[FM translator]].\n{{RadioTranslators\n|callsign        = WKTA\n|call1           = W240DE\n|freq1           = 95.9\n|fid1            = 147928\n|watts1          = 80\n|haat1           = 44\n|class1          = D\n|city1           = Evanston, Illinois\n}}\n\n==History==\nThe station began broadcasting in 1953, holding the call sign WEAW.<ref name=\"BCYearbook1971\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1971/B-1-Radio-YB-1971.pdf 1971 Broadcasting Yearbook]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]], 1971. p. B-63. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> The station was owned by North Shore Broadcasting, and the station's call sign stood for its president Edward A. Wheeler.<ref name=\"Ghrist\"/><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Station-Albums/Chicago-Trib-1979-Mar-About-Chi-Radio.pdf What those letters on the dial mean]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune Magazine]]''. March 4, 1979. p. 16. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> The station's transmitter was located in Evanston and it ran 500 watts during daytime hours only.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> In 1956, the station's power was increased to 1,000 watts.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> By 1959, the station had begun airing brokered ethnic programming.<ref name=\"Ghrist\">Ghrist, John R. (1996). ''Valley Voices: A Radio History''. Crossroads Communications. p. 318-321.</ref> In 1962, the station's transmitter was moved to an unincorporated area between [[Northbrook, Illinois|Northbrook]] and [[Wheeling, Illinois|Wheeling]], and its power was increased to 5,000 watts.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> By the early 1970s the station primarily aired brokered ethnic and religious programs.<ref name=\"Ghrist\"/>\n\nBy early 1979 the station had begun airing a [[Christian contemporary]] format.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Station-Albums/Chicago-Trib-1979-Mar-About-Chi-Radio.pdf Stations, everywhere: a listeners' guide to the AM and FM bands]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune Magazine]]''. March 4, 1979. p. 34. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> On June 1, 1979, the station's call sign was later changed to WPRZ.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/> On July 14, 1979, WPRZ presented the Christian contemporary festival \"Alleluia\", which featured [[Chuck Girard]].<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1979/Billboard%201979-06-30.pdf 'Alleluia' On Air]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. June 30, 1979. p. 20. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> The station was taken off the air in autumn of 1980.<ref name=\"HistoryCards\"/><ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1980s/1980/RR-1980-12-12.pdf '80 In Review]\", ''[[Radio & Records]]'', Issue Number 362, December 12, 1980. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn late 1981, the license was sold to Lee Hague for $125,000.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1981/1981-10-05-BC.pdf Ownership Changes]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. October 5, 1981. p. 59. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> The following year the station was brought back on the air from a new site in the same area, with the WEAW callsign revived.<ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/comment.pl?Application_id=31934&File_number=BMP-19810702AI Public Notice Comment - BMP-19810702AI], fcc.gov. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/comment.pl?Application_id=39083&File_number=BL-19820203AF Public Notice Comment - BL-19820203AF], fcc.gov. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"CallSign\"/> The station aired [[adult contemporary]] music and religious programming.<ref name=\"Ghrist\"/><ref name=\"BCYearbook1983\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1983/B-Radio-Ala-Mt-1983-YB.pdf Broadcasting/Cablecasting Yearbook 1983]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting/Cablecasting]], 1983. p. B-73. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> By the mid-1980s the station was airing [[Christian talk and teaching]] programs and uptempo [[Christian contemporary music]], with a certain amount of secular adult contemporary mixed in.<ref>[[Eric Zorn|Zorn, Eric]]. \"[https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1985-04-14-8501210777-story.html Religious Radio Wades To Mainstream To Pull Listeners To Its Message]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. April 14, 1985. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"ChiRadioGuide\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/Chicago_Magazine/Chicago-Radio-Guide-May-1985.pdf Chicago Radio Guide]''. Vol. 1, No. 1. May 1985. Retrieved September 10, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Ghrist\"/> Christian talk and teaching programs heard on WEAW included ''[[The Old-Time Gospel Hour]]'' with [[Jerry Falwell]], ''Family Altar'' with [[Lester Roloff]], and ''[[Insight for Living]]'' with [[Chuck Swindoll]].<ref name=\"ChiRadioGuide\"/>\n\nIn 1986, the station was sold to Polnet Communications for $1.2 million.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1986/BC-1986-02-17.pdf Changing Hands]\", ''[[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting]]''. February 17, 1986. p. 71. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> The station would air adult contemporary music, along with a large amount of ethnic programming.<ref name=\"BCYearbook1987\">''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1987/B1-BC-YB-1987.pdf Broadcasting/Cablecasting Yearbook 1987]'', [[Broadcasting & Cable|Broadcasting/Cablecasting]], 1987. p. B-89. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref> In October 1987, the station's callsign was changed to WSSY.<ref name=\"CallSign\"/> The station was branded \"Sunny 1330\".<ref>''[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/City-Magazines-Misc/Chicagoland-Radio-Waves-Two-Issues.pdf Chicagoland Radio Waves: Your Complete Guide to Local Radio]''. Media Ties. Summer 1988. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"Ghrist\"/>\n\nIn 1989, WSSY began to air a [[hard rock]] and [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] format branded \"G-Force\", though brokered ethnic and religious programming continued to air mornings and early afternoons.<ref>Seigenthaler, Katherine. \"[https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1990-04-03-9001270499-story.html Heavy Mettle]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. April 3, 1990. Retrieved January 19, 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/Chicago_Magazine/Chicago-1989-Fall.pdf WSSY AM 1330]\", ''Radio Chicago''. Fall 1989. p. 28. Retrieved January 20, 2019.</ref> In 1990 the station's call letters were changed to WKTA.<ref name=\"CallSign\"/> By early 1991, \"G-Force\" had ended, and the station aired brokered ethnic and religious programming.<ref>\"[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Other-Documments/Chicago_Magazine/Chicago-1991-Winter.pdf WKTA AM 1330]\", ''Radio Chicago''. p. 41. Winter 1991. Retrieved January 20, 2019.</ref> The hard rock and heavy metal format would again appear on WKTA as \"Rebel Radio\", a brokered format launched by G-Force alumni Scott Davidson.<ref>[http://www.g-forceradio.zoomshare.com/ Chicago Radio Rock Wars: G-Force 1330] Accessed January 1, 2014</ref> WKTA would become a flagship station for the hard rock network, which was syndicated to other stations in the midwest. [[New Life Russian Radio]] broadcast from [[Northbrook, Illinois]] on 1330 AM WKTA, featuring call-in shows, international news, and European music.<ref>Gwinn, Eric. \"[https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2003-05-02-0305020006-story.html Russian picnic mixes borscht with flavor of the homeland]\", ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. May 2, 2003. Retrieved April 15, 2020.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.facebook.com/pg/ShawnAndMaya/about/ thezone 95.9/1330 Facebook]\n{{AM station data|WKTA}}\n\n{{Chicago Radio}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Radio stations in Chicago|KTA]]\n[[Category:Russian-language radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:German-language radio stations]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language radio stations in Illinois|KTA]]\n[[Category:Foreign-language radio stations in Illinois|KTA]]\n[[Category:Russian-language media in the United States]]\n[[Category:German-language media in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1953]]\n[[Category:1953 establishments in Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Tdl1060", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Removed link to deleted article.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WKTA"}
{"title_page": "The Big Night In", "text_new": "{{distinguish|The Big Night In with John Foreman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| italic_title             = y\n| name                     = The Big Night In\n| image                    = The Big Night In logo.jpg\n| image_upright            = \n| image_size               = 250\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Telethon]]\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Children in Need]] \n* [[Comic Relief]]\n}}\n| developer                = \n| director                 = \n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| executive_producer       = Peter Davey\n| producer                 = Peter Davey\n| editor                   = <!-- Film editors -->\n| camera                   = <!-- Either Single-camera or Multi-camera -->\n| runtime                  = {{Duration|h=3}}\n| company                  = <!-- Production companies only -->\n| distributor              = \n| budget                   = \n| network                  = \n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2020|04|23|df=y}}\n| related                  = <!-- To be used only for remakes, spin-offs, and adaptations -->\n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/bignightin\n| production_website       = <!-- use |production_website_title= to change the display title. -->\n}}\n'''''The Big Night In''''' is a United Kingdom [[telethon]] being broadcast by [[BBC television]] from 7pm to 10pm on 23 April 2020,<ref name=\"Metro-12558735\">{{cite news |title=When is The Big Night In on TV and who is taking part in the BBC One show? |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/15/big-night-tv-taking-part-bbc-one-show-12558735/ |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=Metro |date=15 April 2020 }}</ref> to support those affected by the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Metro-12521241\">{{cite web |title=Children In Need and Comic Relief join forces for first time for coronavirus |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/07/children-need-comic-relief-join-forces-first-time-coronavirus-relief-12521241/ |website=Metro |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Independent-a9474766\">{{cite news |title=BBC Big Night In: Peter Kay, Little Britain and Vicar of Dibley to return for special charity event - follow live |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/bbc-big-night-in-live-stream-channel-best-bits-peter-kay-little-britain-catch-up-watch-a9474766.html |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=23 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The British government will match all public donations, with a minimum of \u00a320 million.<ref name=\"BBC-52379802\">{{cite web |title=Doctor Who stars unite for BBC's Big Night In |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52379802 |website=BBC News |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the first joint initiative between two BBC telethon charities, [[Children in Need]] and [[Comic Relief]].<ref name=\"Metro-12521241\" /> The [[showrunner]] and [[executive producer]] for the BBC is Peter Davey.<ref name=\"YLG2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/leisure/showbiz/18400491.foo-fighters-praise-live-lounge-charity-cover-ahead-bbcs-big-night/|title=Foo Fighters praise Live Lounge charity cover ahead of BBC\u2019s Big Night In|work=Your Local Guardian|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Presenters and performers ==\n\nThe presenters, using [[The One Show]]'s studio  in [[Broadcasting House]], London, include [[Lenny Henry]], with [[Matt Baker]] and [[Davina McCall]] for the first hour and [[Zoe Ball]] and [[Paddy McGuinness]] from 8pm.<ref name=\"Metro-12558735\" />  The studio presenters will maintain [[social distancing]], while most of those appearing will take part remotely, via [[Videotelephony|video links]].<ref name=\"Independent-a9474766\" /> There will be comedy appearances by [[Steve Coogan]], [[Rob Brydon]], [[Jack Whitehall]], [[Romesh Ranganathan]], and [[Miranda Hart]],<ref name=\"BBC-52379802\" /> as well as solo music performances from [[Sam Smith]] and [[Celeste (singer)|Celeste]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bignightin/theshow|title=Big Night In: The Show|website=BBC|url-status=live|access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]] made a surprise appearance, in a sketch with [[Stephen Fry]].<ref name=\"Hill\">{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Rose |title=Prince William surprises Big Night In viewers with Blackadder sketch |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/breaking-prince-william-surprises-big-21917068 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=mirror |date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Line-up ==\n\nFeatured items were:<ref name= \"\">{{Cite episode |title=The Big Night In |series=&nbsp; |serieslink=  |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p088xf57 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |network= [[BBC Television]] |date=23 April 2020 |transcript=  |transcripturl=  }}</ref>\n\n* [[Miranda Hart]] and the cast of ''[[Miranda (TV series)|Miranda]].''\n* [[Sam Smith]] performing \"[[Lay Me Down (Sam Smith song)|Lay Me Down]]\"\n* A lockdown sermon by ''[[The Vicar of Dibley]]'' featuring [[Dawn French]]\n* [[Tess Daly]] and [[Claudia Winkleman]]'s ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' choreography challenge\n* [[Stephen Fry]] as [[List of Blackadder characters#Melchett|Lord Melchett]] ([[Blackadder]]), in conversation with [[William, Duke of Cambridge]]\n* [[Catherine Tate]] and [[David Tennant]] in \"[[Lauren Cooper|Lauren]] the '[[Am I bovvered|Am I Bovvered]]' teenager gets home-schooled\"\n* Premiere of the video for [[Live Lounge Allstars]]' [[Times Like These (Live Lounge Allstars charity single)|cover version]] of [[Foo Fighters]]' \"Times Like These\"\n* [[Romesh Ranganathan]]'s Isolation Diary\n* [[EastEnders]] pub quiz in the [[Queen Vic Fire Week|Queen Vic]] hosted by [[Ian Beale]]\n* Actors who have played the title role in [[Doctor Who]] (original and new series) saluting [[National Health Service|NHS]] health workers\n* [[Little Mix]] offering a prize of a backstage visit to their new TV show\n* [[Matt Lucas]] and the [[BBC Orchestras and Singers|BBC Orchestra]] performing \"Baked Potato Song\"\n* Sports stars undertaking the \"spin challenge\"\n* [[Celeste (singer)|Celeste]] performing a cover of Bill Withers' \"[[Lean on Me (song)|Lean On Me]]\"\n* [[Jack Whitehall]] in [[Bad Education (TV series)|''Bad Education'']] with [[Mathew Horne|Matthew Horne]] and [[Anthony Joshua]]\n* [[Peter Kay]] and the British public remake the \"[[(Is This the Way to) Amarillo|Is This the Way to Amarillo]]\" video\n* [[Joe Wicks (coach)|Joe Wicks]]' exercise secrets\n* The cast of ''[[People Just Do Nothing]]''\n* Stand-up at home from [[Jason Manford]], [[Rosie Jones (comedian)|Rosie Jones]], [[Tim Vine]], [[Tez Ilyas]], [[Dane Baptiste]], [[Russell Kane]], [[Lee Ridley (comedian)|Lost Voice Guy]], [[Nish Kumar]] and more\n\nThere were also guest appearances from [[Jenna Coleman]], [[Tim Cook]], [[Judy Dench]], [[Sting]] and [[Rishi Sunak]].\n\nThe [[BBC]]'s advertised line-up also includes:<ref name=\"Metro-12558735\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52379802\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"ES-LB\">{{cite web |title=Little Britain to return to TV for Big Night In charity telethon |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/little-britain-comeback-big-night-in-bbc-a4416191.html |website=Evening Standard |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Beaumont-Thomas\">{{cite news |last1=Beaumont-Thomas |first1=Ben |title=BBC Radio 1 launches coronavirus charity song with Dua Lipa, Chris Martin and more |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/20/bbc-radio-1-launches-coronavirus-charity-song-with-dua-lipa-chris-martin-and-more |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* [[Steve Coogan]] and [[Rob Brydon]] in ''[[The Trip (2010 TV series)|The Trip]]''\n* The first televisual ''[[Little Britain]]'' sketch for over a decade\n* [[Liam Payne]], [[Olly Murs]], [[Leona Lewis]], [[Nicole Scherzinger]], [[Freya Ridings]], [[Katherine Jenkins]], [[Alfie Boe]], [[Gregory Porter]] and more join [[Gary Barlow]] to perform \"[[Sing (Gary Barlow song)|Sing]]\"\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{BBC programme}}\n*{{IMDb title|tt12183158}}\n<!--\n{{Children in Need}}\n{{Comic Relief}} please wait until after broadcast, so we can make best use of 'what links here' -->\n\n[[Category:Telethons]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Children in Need]]\n[[Category:Comic Relief]]\n[[Category:BBC Television programmes]]\n[[Category:British telethons]]\n[[Category:2020 in British television]]\n[[Category:2020 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:2020 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|The Big Night In with John Foreman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| italic_title             = y\n| name                     = The Big Night In\n| image                    = The Big Night In logo.jpg\n| image_upright            = \n| image_size               = 250\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Telethon]]\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Children in Need]] \n* [[Comic Relief]]\n}}\n| developer                = \n| director                 = \n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| executive_producer       = Peter Davey\n| producer                 = Peter Davey\n| editor                   = <!-- Film editors -->\n| camera                   = <!-- Either Single-camera or Multi-camera -->\n| runtime                  = {{Duration|h=3}}\n| company                  = <!-- Production companies only -->\n| distributor              = \n| budget                   = \n| network                  = \n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2020|04|23|df=y}}\n| related                  = <!-- To be used only for remakes, spin-offs, and adaptations -->\n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/bignightin\n| production_website       = <!-- use |production_website_title= to change the display title. -->\n}}\n'''''The Big Night In''''' is a United Kingdom [[telethon]] being broadcast by [[BBC television]] from 7pm to 10pm on 23 April 2020,<ref name=\"Metro-12558735\">{{cite news |title=When is The Big Night In on TV and who is taking part in the BBC One show? |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/15/big-night-tv-taking-part-bbc-one-show-12558735/ |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=Metro |date=15 April 2020 }}</ref> to support those affected by the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Metro-12521241\">{{cite web |title=Children In Need and Comic Relief join forces for first time for coronavirus |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/07/children-need-comic-relief-join-forces-first-time-coronavirus-relief-12521241/ |website=Metro |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Independent-a9474766\">{{cite news |title=BBC Big Night In: Peter Kay, Little Britain and Vicar of Dibley to return for special charity event - follow live |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/bbc-big-night-in-live-stream-channel-best-bits-peter-kay-little-britain-catch-up-watch-a9474766.html |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=23 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The British government will match all public donations, with a minimum of \u00a320 million.<ref name=\"BBC-52379802\">{{cite web |title=Doctor Who stars unite for BBC's Big Night In |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52379802 |website=BBC News |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the first joint initiative between two BBC telethon charities, [[Children in Need]] and [[Comic Relief]].<ref name=\"Metro-12521241\" /> The [[showrunner]] and [[executive producer]] for the BBC is Peter Davey.<ref name=\"YLG2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/leisure/showbiz/18400491.foo-fighters-praise-live-lounge-charity-cover-ahead-bbcs-big-night/|title=Foo Fighters praise Live Lounge charity cover ahead of BBC\u2019s Big Night In|work=Your Local Guardian|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Presenters and performers ==\n\nThe presenters, using [[The One Show]]'s studio  in [[Broadcasting House]], London, include [[Lenny Henry]], with [[Matt Baker]] and [[Davina McCall]] for the first hour and [[Zoe Ball]] and [[Paddy McGuinness]] from 8pm.<ref name=\"Metro-12558735\" />  The studio presenters will maintain [[social distancing]], while most of those appearing will take part remotely, via [[Videotelephony|video links]].<ref name=\"Independent-a9474766\" /> There will be comedy appearances by [[Steve Coogan]], [[Rob Brydon]], [[Jack Whitehall]], [[Romesh Ranganathan]], and [[Miranda Hart]],<ref name=\"BBC-52379802\" /> as well as solo music performances from [[Sam Smith]] and [[Celeste (singer)|Celeste]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bignightin/theshow|title=Big Night In: The Show|website=BBC|url-status=live|access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]] made a surprise appearance, in a sketch with [[Stephen Fry]].<ref name=\"Hill\">{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Rose |title=Prince William surprises Big Night In viewers with Blackadder sketch |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/breaking-prince-william-surprises-big-21917068 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=mirror |date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Line-up ==\n\nFeatured items were:<ref name= \"\">{{Cite episode |title=The Big Night In |series=&nbsp; |serieslink=  |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p088xf57 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |network= [[BBC Television]] |date=23 April 2020 |transcript=  |transcripturl=  }}</ref>\n\n* [[Miranda Hart]] and the cast of ''[[Miranda (TV series)|Miranda]].''\n* [[Sam Smith]] performing \"[[Lay Me Down (Sam Smith song)|Lay Me Down]]\"\n* A lockdown sermon by ''[[The Vicar of Dibley]]'' featuring [[Dawn French]]\n* [[Tess Daly]] and [[Claudia Winkleman]]'s ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' choreography challenge\n* [[Stephen Fry]] as [[List of Blackadder characters#Melchett|Lord Melchett]] ([[Blackadder]]), in conversation with [[William, Duke of Cambridge]]\n* [[Catherine Tate]] and [[David Tennant]] in \"[[Lauren Cooper|Lauren]] the '[[Am I bovvered|Am I Bovvered]]' teenager gets home-schooled\"\n* Premiere of the video for [[Live Lounge Allstars]]' [[Times Like These (Live Lounge Allstars charity single)|cover version]] of [[Foo Fighters]]' \"Times Like These\"\n* [[Romesh Ranganathan]]'s Isolation Diary\n* [[EastEnders]] pub quiz in the [[Queen Vic Fire Week|Queen Vic]] hosted by [[Ian Beale]]\n* Actors who have played the title role in [[Doctor Who]] (original and new series) saluting [[National Health Service|NHS]] health workers\n* [[Little Mix]] offering a prize of a backstage visit to their new TV show\n* [[Matt Lucas]] and the [[BBC Orchestras and Singers|BBC Orchestra]] performing \"Baked Potato Song\"\n* Sports stars undertaking the \"spin challenge\"\n* [[Celeste (singer)|Celeste]] performing a cover of Bill Withers' \"[[Lean on Me (song)|Lean On Me]]\"\n* [[Jack Whitehall]] in [[Bad Education (TV series)|''Bad Education'']] with [[Mathew Horne|Matthew Horne]] and [[Anthony Joshua]]\n* [[Peter Kay]] and the British public remake the \"[[(Is This the Way to) Amarillo|Is This the Way to Amarillo]]\" video\n* [[Joe Wicks (coach)|Joe Wicks]]' exercise secrets\n* The cast of ''[[People Just Do Nothing]]''\n* Stand-up at home from [[Jason Manford]], [[Rosie Jones (comedian)|Rosie Jones]], [[Tim Vine]], [[Tez Ilyas]], [[Dane Baptiste]], [[Russell Kane]], [[Lee Ridley (comedian)|Lost Voice Guy]]], [[Nish Kumar]] and more\n\nThere were also guest appearances from [[Jenna Coleman]], [[Tim Cook]], [[Judy Dench]], [[Sting]] and [[Rishi Sunak]].\n\nThe [[BBC]]'s advertised line-up also includes:<ref name=\"Metro-12558735\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52379802\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"ES-LB\">{{cite web |title=Little Britain to return to TV for Big Night In charity telethon |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/little-britain-comeback-big-night-in-bbc-a4416191.html |website=Evening Standard |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Beaumont-Thomas\">{{cite news |last1=Beaumont-Thomas |first1=Ben |title=BBC Radio 1 launches coronavirus charity song with Dua Lipa, Chris Martin and more |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/20/bbc-radio-1-launches-coronavirus-charity-song-with-dua-lipa-chris-martin-and-more |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* [[Steve Coogan]] and [[Rob Brydon]] in ''[[The Trip (2010 TV series)|The Trip]]''\n* The first televisual ''[[Little Britain]]'' sketch for over a decade\n* [[Liam Payne]], [[Olly Murs]], [[Leona Lewis]], [[Nicole Scherzinger]], [[Freya Ridings]], [[Katherine Jenkins]], [[Alfie Boe]], [[Gregory Porter]] and more join [[Gary Barlow]] to perform \"[[Sing (Gary Barlow song)|Sing]]\"\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{BBC programme}}\n*{{IMDb title|tt12183158}}\n<!--\n{{Children in Need}}\n{{Comic Relief}} please wait until after broadcast, so we can make best use of 'what links here' -->\n\n[[Category:Telethons]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Children in Need]]\n[[Category:Comic Relief]]\n[[Category:BBC Television programmes]]\n[[Category:British telethons]]\n[[Category:2020 in British television]]\n[[Category:2020 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:2020 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Pigsonthewing", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLine-up:c", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Big_Night_In"}
{"title_page": "Alice Marian Ellen Bale", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox artist\n| name           = Alice Marion Ellen Bale\n| image          = Alice_Marian_Ellen_Bale_self_portrait.jpg\n| imagesize      =\n| caption        = Self portrait\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|df=yes|1875|11|11}}\n| birth_place    = Richmond, Australia\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|df=yes|1955|2|14|1875|11|11}}\n| death_place   = Melbourne, Australia<ref name=\"ADB\"/>\n| nationality   = Australian\n| education     = National Gallery of Victoria Art School\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      =\n| movement      = \n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| awards        = \n| spouse        = \n\n}}\n\n'''Alice Marion Ellen Bale''' , or '''A.M.E. Bale''', (11 November 1875 {{ndash}} 14 February 1955)<ref>''Victoria, Australia, Cemetery Records and Headstone Transcriptions, 1844-1997''</ref> was an [[Australian]] artist.\n\nBale was born in Richmond, Victoria<ref name=\"ADB\">{{cite web|last1=McGrath|first1=Joyce|title=Bale, Alice Marian Ellen (1875\u20131955)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/bale-alice-marian-ellen-5113|website=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=Australian National University|accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref>, the daughter of naturalist William Mountier Bale.<ref>{{cite web|title=William Mountier Bale (1851\u20131940)|url=https://museumvictoria.com.au/treasures/collDetails.aspx?Simg=4&PID=72|publisher=Victoria Museum|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> She studied art under [[Frederick McCubbin]] and [[Lindsay Bernard Hall]] at the [[National Gallery of Victoria Art School|National Gallery School]] 1895{{ndash}}1904.  She came to prominence as an artist in [[Melbourne]] in the 1920s and 1930s, developing a reputation as one of Australia's pre-eminent flower and still life painters.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Perry, Peter | title=A M E Bale : her art and life | publication-date=2011 | publisher=Castlemaine Art Gallery and Historical Museum | edition=Limited | isbn=978-0-9757388-7-0 }}</ref><ref name=GlenEira2016>{{Citation |url= http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/Places-and-events/Arts-and-Culture/Galleries-and-Visual-Art/AME-Bale |title= 2016 A.M.E. Bale Travelling Scholarship and Art Prize |publisher= Glen Eira City Council }}</ref>  \n\nShe was the founding secretary of the [[Twenty Melbourne Painters Society]], a position that she held until her death.<ref name=Guidelines>[http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/files/assets/public/document-resources/arts-and-culture/ame-bale-guidelines.pdf Guidelines], AME Bale Art Prizes, www.gleneira.vic.gov.au</ref>\n\nShe exhibited with the [[Melbourne Society of Women Painters and Sculptors|Melbourne Society of Women Painters]] 1917{{ndash}}1955.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Peers, Juliette | title=More than just gumtrees : a personal, social and artistic history of the Melbourne Society of Women Painters and Sculptors | publication-date=1993 | publisher=Melbourne Society of Women Painters and Sculptors in association with Dawn Revival Press | isbn=978-0-646-16033-7 }}</ref>\n\n==AME Bale Travelling Scholarship and Art Prize==\nBale established the biennial A.M.E. Bale Travelling Scholarship and Art Prize through her will to support Australian artists in perpetuity. The prize \"is intended to encourage, support and advance classical training of emerging artists (in their early to mid-career) at any stage of life, who are pursuing the study and practice of traditional art and who desire to study the works of old masters\".<ref name=GlenEira2016/><ref name=Guidelines/>\n\nThree prizes are awarded:<ref name=GlenEira2016/>\n* Major Award for a Travelling Scholarship (AU$50,000) since 2011<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://joshuamcpherson.com/files/media011210a.pdf |title=2010 A.M.E. Bale Travelling Scholarship and Art Prize |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20111216120832/http://joshuamcpherson.com/files/media011210a.pdf |archive-date=16 December 2011 |access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref>  \n* A.M.E. Bale Art Prize in the medium of oil and/or acrylic (AU$5,000)\n* A.M.E. Bale Art Prize for Works on Paper (AU$5,000)\n\nAward winners: \n[http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/Places-and-events/Arts-and-Culture/Galleries-and-Visual-Art/AME-Bale 2016];\n[http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/Places-and-events/Arts-and-Culture/Art-awards/A.M.E.-Bale-Travelling-Scholarship-and-Art-Prize/A.M.E.-Bale-Travelling-Scholarship-and-Art-Prize-winners-2014 2014];\n[http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/Places-and-events/Arts-and-Culture/Art-awards/A.M.E.-Bale-Travelling-Scholarship-and-Art-Prize/A.M.E.-Bale-Travelling-Scholarship-and-Art-Prize-winners-2012 2012];\n[http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/Places-and-events/Arts-and-Culture/Art-awards/A.M.E.-Bale-Travelling-Scholarship-and-Art-Prize/A.M.E-Bale-Travelling-Scholarship-and-Art-Prize-winners-2011 2011]\n== In collections==\nShe has work in the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]],<ref name=agnsw>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/collection/works/?artist_id=bale-ame|title=Works by A.M.E. Bale :: The Collection :: Art Gallery NSW|website=www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> and the [[National Gallery of Victoria]]''.''<ref name=ngv>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ngv.vic.gov.au/explore/collection/artist/1856/|title=A. M. E. BALE {{!}} Artists {{!}} NGV|website=www.ngv.vic.gov.au|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> \n==Awards==\nShe was a finalist in the [[Archibald Prize]] in 1922,<ref name=AP1922>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/prizes/archibald/1922/14654/|title=Archibald Prize Archibald 1922 finalist: Portrait Miss Jo Sweatman by A M E Bale|last=Deutsch|last2=Fran\u00e7ais|website=www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au|access-date=2019-08-24|last3=\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e|last4=\u4e2d\u6587|last5=Espa\u00f1ol|last6=Italiano|last7=\ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4|last8=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|last9=us|first9=Contact}}</ref> and 1924,<ref name=AP1924>{{Cite web|url= https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/prizes/archibald/1924/14657/| title=Archibald Prize Archibald 1924 finalist: Miss Clive Walsh by A M E Bale|last=Deutsch|last2=Fran\u00e7ais|website=www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au|access-date=2019-08-24|last3=\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e|last4=\u4e2d\u6587|last5=Espa\u00f1ol|last6=Italiano|last7=\ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4|last8=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|last9=us|first9=Contact}}</ref> while 1932 [[Ernest Buckmaster]]'s portrait of her was a finalist in the Archibald.<ref name=AP1932>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/prizes/archibald/1932/14954/|title=Archibald Prize Archibald 1932 finalist: Miss AME Bale by Ernest Buckmaster|last=Deutsch|last2=Fran\u00e7ais|website=www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au|access-date=2019-08-24|last3=\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e|last4=\u4e2d\u6587|last5=Espa\u00f1ol|last6=Italiano|last7=\ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4|last8=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|last9=us|first9=Contact}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bale, Alice}}\n[[Category:Australian women painters]]\n[[Category:Heidelberg School]]\n[[Category:Artists from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian artists]]\n[[Category:Archibald Prize finalists]]\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox artist\n| name           = Alice Marion Ellen Bale\n| image          = Alice_Marian_Ellen_Bale_self_portrait.jpg\n| imagesize      =\n| caption        = Self portrait\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|df=yes|1875|11|11}}\n| birth_place    = Richmond, Australia\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|df=yes|1955|2|14|1875|11|11}}\n| death_place   = Melbourne, Australia<ref name=\"ADB\"/>\n| nationality   = Australian\n| education     = National Gallery of Victoria Art School\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      =\n| movement      = \n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| awards        = \n| spouse        = \n\n}}\n\n'''Alice Marion Ellen Bale''' , or '''A.M.E. Bale''', (11 November 1875 {{ndash}} 14 February 1955)<ref>''Victoria, Australia, Cemetery Records and Headstone Transcriptions, 1844-1997''</ref> was an [[Australian]] artist.\n\nBale was born in Richmond, Victoria<ref name=\"ADB\">{{cite web|last1=McGrath|first1=Joyce|title=Bale, Alice Marian Ellen (1875\u20131955)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/bale-alice-marian-ellen-5113|website=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=Australian National University|accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref>, the daughter of naturalist William Mountier Bale.<ref>{{cite web|title=William Mountier Bale (1851\u20131940)|url=https://museumvictoria.com.au/treasures/collDetails.aspx?Simg=4&PID=72|publisher=Victoria Museum|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> She studied art under [[Frederick McCubbin]] and [[Lindsay Bernard Hall]] at the [[National Gallery of Victoria Art School|National Gallery School]] 1895{{ndash}}1904.  She came to prominence as an artist in [[Melbourne]] in the 1920s and 1930s, developing a reputation as one of Australia's pre-eminent flower and still life painters.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Perry, Peter | title=A M E Bale : her art and life | publication-date=2011 | publisher=Castlemaine Art Gallery and Historical Museum | edition=Limited | isbn=978-0-9757388-7-0 }}</ref><ref name=GlenEira2016>{{Citation |url= http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/Places-and-events/Arts-and-Culture/Galleries-and-Visual-Art/AME-Bale |title= 2016 A.M.E. Bale Travelling Scholarship and Art Prize |publisher= Glen Eira City Council }}</ref>  \n\nShe was the founding secretary of the [[Twenty Melbourne Painters Society]], a position that she held until her death.<ref name=Guidelines>[http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/files/assets/public/document-resources/arts-and-culture/ame-bale-guidelines.pdf Guidelines], AME Bale Art Prizes, www.gleneira.vic.gov.au</ref>\n\nShe exhibited with the [[Melbourne Society of Women Painters and Sculptors|Melbourne Society of Women Painters]] 1917{{ndash}}1955.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Peers, Juliette | title=More than just gumtrees : a personal, social and artistic history of the Melbourne Society of Women Painters and Sculptors | publication-date=1993 | publisher=Melbourne Society of Women Painters and Sculptors in association with Dawn Revival Press | isbn=978-0-646-16033-7 }}</ref>\n\n==AME Bale Travelling Scholarship and Art Prize==\nBale established the biennial A.M.E. Bale Travelling Scholarship and Art Prize through her will to support Australian artists in perpetuity. The prize \"is intended to encourage, support and advance classical training of emerging artists (in their early to mid-career) at any stage of life, who are pursuing the study and practice of traditional art and who desire to study the works of old masters\".<ref name=GlenEira2016/><ref name=Guidelines/>\n\nThree prizes are awarded:<ref name=GlenEira2016/>\n* Major Award for a Travelling Scholarship (AU$50,000) since 2011<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://joshuamcpherson.com/files/media011210a.pdf |title=2010 A.M.E. Bale Travelling Scholarship and Art Prize |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20111216120832/http://joshuamcpherson.com/files/media011210a.pdf |archive-date=16 December 2011 |access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref>  \n* A.M.E. Bale Art Prize in the medium of oil and/or acrylic (AU$5,000)\n* A.M.E. Bale Art Prize for Works on Paper (AU$5,000)\n\nAward winners: \n[http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/Places-and-events/Arts-and-Culture/Galleries-and-Visual-Art/AME-Bale 2016];\n[http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/Places-and-events/Arts-and-Culture/Art-awards/A.M.E.-Bale-Travelling-Scholarship-and-Art-Prize/A.M.E.-Bale-Travelling-Scholarship-and-Art-Prize-winners-2014 2014];\n[http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/Places-and-events/Arts-and-Culture/Art-awards/A.M.E.-Bale-Travelling-Scholarship-and-Art-Prize/A.M.E.-Bale-Travelling-Scholarship-and-Art-Prize-winners-2012 2012];\n[http://www.gleneira.vic.gov.au/Places-and-events/Arts-and-Culture/Art-awards/A.M.E.-Bale-Travelling-Scholarship-and-Art-Prize/A.M.E-Bale-Travelling-Scholarship-and-Art-Prize-winners-2011 2011]\n== In collections==\nShe has work in the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]],<ref name=agnsw>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/collection/works/?artist_id=bale-ame|title=Works by A.M.E. Bale :: The Collection :: Art Gallery NSW|website=www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> and the [[National Gallery of Victoria]]''.''<ref name=ngv>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ngv.vic.gov.au/explore/collection/artist/1856/|title=A. M. E. BALE {{!}} Artists {{!}} NGV|website=www.ngv.vic.gov.au|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> \n==Awards==\nShe was a finalist in the [[Archibald Prize]] in 1922,<ref name=AP1922>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/prizes/archibald/1922/14654/|title=Archibald Prize Archibald 1922 finalist: Portrait Miss Jo Sweatman by A M E Bale|last=Deutsch|last2=Fran\u00e7ais|website=www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au|access-date=2019-08-24|last3=\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e|last4=\u4e2d\u6587|last5=Espa\u00f1ol|last6=Italiano|last7=\ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4|last8=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|last9=us|first9=Contact}}</ref> and 1924,<ref name=AP1924>{{Cite web|url= https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/prizes/archibald/1924/14657/| title=Archibald Prize Archibald 1924 finalist: Miss Clive Walsh by A M E Bale|last=Deutsch|last2=Fran\u00e7ais|website=www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au|access-date=2019-08-24|last3=\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e|last4=\u4e2d\u6587|last5=Espa\u00f1ol|last6=Italiano|last7=\ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4|last8=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|last9=us|first9=Contact}}</ref> while 1932 [[Ernest Buckmaster]]'s portrait of her was a finalist in the Archibald.<ref name=AP1932>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/prizes/archibald/1932/14954/|title=Archibald Prize Archibald 1932 finalist: Miss AME Bale by Ernest Buckmaster|last=Deutsch|last2=Fran\u00e7ais|website=www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au|access-date=2019-08-24|last3=\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e|last4=\u4e2d\u6587|last5=Espa\u00f1ol|last6=Italiano|last7=\ud55c\uad6d\uc5b4|last8=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|last9=us|first9=Contact}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bale, Alice}}\n[[Category:Australian women painters]]\n[[Category:Heidelberg School]]\n[[Category:Artists from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women artists]]\n[[Category:Archibald Prize finalists]]\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian women]]\n", "name_user": "Chris.sherlock", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(fix cats)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_Marian_Ellen_Bale"}
